Following motorcycle, tricycle restriction in Lagos State, the Lagos Chamber of Commerce and Industry (LCCI) has recommended an urgent stakeholder engagement to fine tune the traffic law and enforcement strategies. The director-general of LCCI, Muda Yusuf said that one of the biggest challenges of urbanisation is traffic congestion and this is more so in a state like Lagos which has the largest population and the smallest land size in the country. He noted that the growth in the number of vehicles has consistently outpaced the road capacity, saying that “We also recognise the increasing traffic and security nuisance that some of the commercial motorcycles and tricycles create in the state and these call for drastic action by the government.” He said that it is important to situate the conversation within the context of a Root Cause Analysis. According to Yusuf, the proliferation of the commercial motorcycles and tricycles in Lagos state are manifestation of the shortcomings of the transportation system in Lagos state and are symptoms of deeper issues in the transport ecosystem. He stated that there are fundamentals issues the state needs to fix in order to achieve a sustainable solution. “The enforcement of the traffic law in its current form would have a profound social, economic and political costs. “Commuters would suffer untold hardship as there is no immediate alternative to fill the gap which the wide-ranging restriction would create. “There would be high transportation cost as commuter buses hikes their fares and they would naturally take advantage of the surge in demand. “There is also the investment effect on emerging innovative investments in the commercial motorbike sector some of which have invested billions of Naira in the sector. “Connectivity of domestic economic agents would suffer a deceleration.  The tempo and momentum of economic activities would experience a slow down as the velocity of business transactions would be adversely affected.’’ 